<TITLE> Kirsten says not a candidate for England job </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 CHENNAI, India, April 2 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - India cricket coach Gary Kirsten says he is not a candidate for the England position left vacant by the sacking of Peter Moores, website www.cricinfo.com reported on Thursday. The England and Wales Cricket Board (ECB) is engaged in finding a successor to Moores and the former South Africa opener has been linked to the job by the British media. "I am not a candidate," Kirsten told the website, adding that he had not been contacted by the ECB. Kirsten's two-year contract with the Board of Control in India (BCCI) runs until March next year and BCCI officials dismissed the link with the England job as baseless. "I refuse to even comment," BCCI secretary N. Srinivasan told Reuters on Thursday. Kirsten took over from Greg Chappell and has helped the Indian team improve their performances, earning the respect of the players for his quiet approach following a turbulent period under the Australian. Kirsten is currently in New Zealand with the Indian team, who start the third test on Friday needing a draw to clinch the series
